### Reading Files

The `ifstream` class is used for reading data from files.

---

### Reading Line by Line

```cpp
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

ifstream file("data.txt");
string line;

while (getline(file, line)) {
  cout << line << endl;
}
```

---

### Reading Word by Word

```cpp
ifstream file("words.txt");
string word;

while (file >> word) {
  cout << word << " ";
}
```

---

### Reading Character by Character

```cpp
ifstream file("text.txt");
char ch;

while (file.get(ch)) {
  cout << ch;
}
```

---

### Reading Entire File into String

```cpp
#include <sstream>

ifstream file("data.txt");
stringstream buffer;
buffer << file.rdbuf();
string content = buffer.str();
```

---

### Checking End of File

```cpp
while (!file.eof()) {
  string line;
  getline(file, line);
  cout << line;  // Note: eof() only set after failed read
}
```

---

> **Key Point:** Use `getline(file, line)` for line-by-line reading. The `>>` operator reads tokens separated by whitespace. Always check if the file opened successfully before reading.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  ifstream file("example.txt");

  if (file.is_open()) {
    string line;
    while (getline(file, line)) {
      cout << line << endl;
    }
    file.close();
  } else {
    cout << "Unable to open file" << endl;
  }
  return 0;
}
